         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0141">
               <p>Born in <placeName>Newcastle upon Tyne</placeName>, in <date when="1736"
                     >1736</date> Grace Norman married <persName>Alexander Murray</persName>, a
                  seaman, who died six years later. She first heard <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> preach in
                     <placeName>Moorfields</placeName> on <date when="1739-09-09">Sept. 9,
                     1739</date>, and in the early <date>1740s</date> was a member of bands for
                  married women at the Foundery. After her husband&apos;s death <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> made her housekeeper at the
                  Orphan House in <placeName>Newcastle</placeName>. She accompanied <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> on a preaching tour in
                     <placeName>Ireland</placeName> in <date when="1748">1748</date>, during which
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> suggested the
                  possibility of their marriage. This was not to be, largely through the
                  intervention of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>, who
                  solemnized the marriage of Grace to <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0143.xml"
                     />John Bennet</persName> on <date when="1749-10-03">Oct. 3, 1749</date>. See
                     <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 808; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                  >Dictionary</hi>, 248.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
